---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { useCaseBySlug } from '../../data/use-cases';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const uc = useCaseBySlug('browse-abandonment')!;
const path = '/use-cases/browse-abandonment';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'use-cases/browse-abandonment');
const desc = description(site, 'use-cases/browse-abandonment');

const featuredSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'yotpo-email-sms'];
const featuredApps = featuredSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const comparisonApps = [
  'sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'yotpo-email-sms', 'shopify-email',
  'mailchimp', 'activecampaign', 'brevo', 'firepush',
].map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is the best Shopify email tool for browse abandonment?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy ranks first for browse programs that need proof-before-discount logic and product-specific education blocks — ideal for specialty tea, climbing gear, and vinyl where research intent dominates. Klaviyo wins at scale with view-depth triggers, dynamic product feeds, and predictive conversion scoring across large catalogs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How is browse abandonment different from cart abandonment?',
    answer: 'Browse abandoners showed interest without checkout intent. Cart abandoners nearly purchased. Browse flows use longer delays, education-first creative, and discounts only on later touches. Merging the two trains discount waiting and inflates unsubscribe rates on high-consideration products.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should the first browse abandonment email send?',
    answer: 'Four to six hours after the qualifying product view for most DTC. High-AOV outdoor gear and custom pottery may delay to 12–24 hours. First email should lead with social proof and usage context, not a coupon. Second email at 48 hours adds education; discount only in email three if engagement stays cold.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What trigger threshold reduces browse email noise?',
    answer: 'Require two product views or 60+ seconds on PDP before enrollment. Single-page bounces from paid social should not enter browse flows. Klaviyo and Sequenzy both support view-count and dwell-time conditions when onsite tracking is configured correctly.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should browse emails recommend out-of-stock variants?',
    answer: 'Never. Filter recommendations to in-stock SKUs only. If the browsed variant is OOS, swap to alternatives or route to back-in-stock waitlist. Sending browse recovery for unavailable products — limited tea harvests, sold-out vinyl pressings — destroys credibility faster than silence.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can browse abandonment work without discounts?',
    answer: 'Yes, and it should for full-price loyal segments. A specialty tea merchant recovering 4.2% of browse sessions with education-only emails outperformed their old instant-10% flow on margin. Reserve discounts for cold segments with prior discount redemption history.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do browse and cart flows interact?',
    answer: 'Cart flow takes priority. Suppress browse discount emails while a customer is active in cart recovery. If someone browses then carts, exit browse path at add-to-cart. Document collision rules before launch — overlap causes double-touch fatigue.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Shopify Email support browse abandonment automation?',
    answer: 'No meaningful browse automation. Shopify Email lacks behavioral view triggers, dynamic product blocks from browse history, and multi-touch nurture with suppression. Dedicated lifecycle platforms are standard once browse recovery exceeds casual campaign sends.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/use-cases" class="text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16] hover:text-[#24170f]">← All use cases</a>
      <p class="catalog-kicker mt-6">Browse abandonment</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Best Shopify email tools for browse abandonment</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Browse abandonment sits between newsletter discovery and cart intent — the hardest lifecycle moment to get right. A specialty tea subscriber reading origin notes on a limited oolong needs proof and brewing context, not a coupon within four hours. The right Shopify email tool follows product interest with education, pulls live reviews into dynamic blocks, and saves discounts for subscribers who still have not moved after genuine research time.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        This playbook ranks email tools for {uc.job}. We evaluated view-depth triggers, OOS filtering, collision with cart flows, and whether operators can rewrite browse logic when seasonal catalogs rotate — not which platform has the flashiest product grid templates.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Full tool catalog</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo">Sequenzy vs Klaviyo</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="Top Shopify email tools for browse abandonment"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Best overall', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Browse playbooks with proof-first sequencing, education blocks, and discount delay logic for research-heavy catalogs.' },
        { label: 'Best data depth', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'View-depth triggers, dynamic product feeds, and predictive conversion scoring at catalog scale.' },
        { label: 'Best workflow control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual browse branches by product category, view count, and engagement tier with explicit wait steps.' },
        { label: 'Best fast setup', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt browse journeys with SMS branch when email unopened after first touch.' },
        { label: 'Best social proof', tool: 'Yotpo Email & SMS', reason: 'Native review and UGC blocks in browse emails when proof drives conversion more than discounts.' },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Three browse abandonment merchant scenarios</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — Specialty tea merchant, limited harvest PDP views.</strong> Sequenzy browse flow: email one at 6 hours with origin story and steeping guide; email two at 48 hours with customer tasting notes; discount only in email three for non-openers. Browse-to-cart rate rose 14% versus their old instant-coupon browse flow, with 31% higher full-price conversion on recovered sessions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — Climbing gear shop, harness comparison browsing.</strong> Klaviyo enrolled viewers who spent 90+ seconds on two harness PDPs. Dynamic block pulled reviews mentioning fit and gym use. OOS color variant filtered automatically. Education-first path recovered 5.8% of browse revenue without discount on first touch — critical when safety specs drive purchase decisions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — Vinyl record shop, genre collection browsing.</strong> Drip tagged browse by genre metafield — jazz viewers received pressing quality education; electronic viewers received artist interview content. No discount until email three. Newsletter subscribers who browsed converted at 2.1× rate versus cold browse-only profiles when editorial tone matched genre interest.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Execution playbook</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse abandonment operating contract</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Trigger</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.trigger}</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Timing</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.timing}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Exclusions</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.exclusions.map((e) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{e}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Metrics</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.metrics.map((m) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{m}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Common mistakes: {uc.mistakes.join('; ')}. See <a class="link" href="/use-cases/reviews-and-ugc">reviews and UGC</a> for proof block setup.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12 overflow-x-auto">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Comparison table</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">10 Shopify email tools for browse abandonment</h2>
      <table class="mt-8 w-full min-w-[720px] text-left text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/15 text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-wider text-[#9a5b16]">
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">App</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Browse fit</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Pricing</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Shopify depth</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Automation</th>
            <th class="py-3">Rating</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-[#4a2d17]">
          {comparisonApps.map((app, i) => (
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold text-[#24170f]"><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{i + 1}. {app.name}</a></td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.bestFor}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.pricing}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.shopifyDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.automationDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3">★ {app.rating}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container space-y-12 pb-16">
    <p class="catalog-kicker">Detailed reviews</p>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Five apps for browse abandonment</h2>

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[0]}
      rank={1}
      badge="Editor's choice"
      paragraphs={[
        'Sequenzy leads browse abandonment because the default failure is discounting research intent. Teams blast 10% off within two hours of a PDP view — then wonder why full-price newsletter sends underperform. Sequenzy browse playbooks encode proof-first sequencing, category-specific education, and discount delay until email three for cold segments.',
        'Browse flows are lower volume than cart but higher risk for brand positioning. Pay-per-email pricing lets you run education-heavy three-touch browse without per-contact bill shock when view events inflate profile counts. Sequenzy unlimited contacts support aggressive suppression without deleting profiles to save money.',
        'Collision suppression with cart and welcome is explicit — browse exits at add-to-cart, cart wins when both active. Agent-first edits let operators say "tea harvest browse gets brewing guide email one, climbing harness browse gets fit FAQ" without rebuilding boolean trees.',
        'Pair Sequenzy with Yotpo when review-rich browse emails outperform generic product grids — especially for pottery glazes and outdoor gear where customer photos drive trust.',
        'Operational note for browse abandonment: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Sequenzy implementation for browse abandonment should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on browse abandonment flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[1]}
      rank={2}
      paragraphs={[
        'Klaviyo browse abandonment is the scale benchmark. View-depth triggers, dynamic product feeds from browse history, and category-level segmentation recover high-SKU catalogs where generic reminders fail.',
        'Predictive analytics identify browse sessions likely to convert without discount — full-price paths for engaged openers, soft incentive only for predicted discount-sensitive profiles. Margin on browse-recovered revenue rose 24% for a board game publisher versus blanket browse discounting.',
        'Flow A/B testing on education versus product-grid-first email one is mature. Revenue per recipient by variant beats click rate for browse decisions — researchers click education links; impulse browsers click product grids.',
        'Profile pricing stings when browse viewers include paid-social bouncers synced as profiles. Tighten enrollment thresholds and sunset non-engaged browse profiles after 90 days.',
        'Operational note for browse abandonment: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Klaviyo implementation for browse abandonment should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on browse abandonment flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[2]}
      rank={3}
      paragraphs={[
        'Drip visual browse workflows suit operators who want explicit branches: single view versus repeat view, category tag from collection URL, newsletter subscriber versus anonymous browser.',
        'Tag triggers enrich browse emails — "browsed-mechanical-keyboard" tag adds switch compatibility guide block. Revenue dashboard attributes browse paths clearly for weekly optimization.',
        'Drip lacks Klaviyo predictive layer — use engagement tags manually for discount sensitivity. Strong for focused enthusiast catalogs under 800 SKUs.',
        'Pick Drip when someone on the team enjoys canvas workflow design and browse needs custom category logic Omnisend resists.',
        'Operational note for browse abandonment: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Drip implementation for browse abandonment should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on browse abandonment flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[3]}
      rank={4}
      paragraphs={[
        'Omnisend prebuilt browse series is the fastest path live — two emails and optional SMS in under a day. Acceptable when browse logic is standard and catalog inventory is stable.',
        'SMS branch when email one unopened after 24 hours recovers mobile researchers — useful for outdoor gear flash browsing. Discipline required: SMS overuse on browse feels more invasive than cart SMS.',
        'Omnisend exclusion visibility is weaker than Klaviyo for multi-flow suppression — manual tags needed when customers sit in browse and winback simultaneously.',
        'Graduate to Sequenzy or Klaviyo when browse paths need category-specific education beyond template splits.',
        'Operational note for browse abandonment: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Omnisend implementation for browse abandonment should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on browse abandonment flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[4]}
      rank={5}
      paragraphs={[
        'Yotpo Email & SMS shines when browse conversion depends on social proof more than discounts. Native review and UGC blocks pull live content into browse emails without manual HTML.',
        'Star-rating filters let browse emails show reviews matching browsed product attributes — harness fit reviews for climbing gear, tasting notes for specialty tea. Conversion lift measurable when proof blocks replace generic hero images.',
        'Yotpo is not a full lifecycle platform alone — pair with Sequenzy or Klaviyo for trigger logic, suppression, and discount escalation rules.',
        'Best for catalogs with rich review volume where browse objection is trust, not price.',
        'Operational note for browse abandonment: suppression between promotional newsletters and active automations prevents margin erosion when subscribers receive stacked incentives. Weekly fifteen-minute flow collision audit beats quarterly emergency discount review.',
        'Pair with capture tooling (Privy, Justuno) when list growth outpaces purchase conversion — ESP depth only matters after opt-in volume justifies segmentation. Measure revenue per recipient by cohort monthly, not broadcast open rate alone.',
        'Yotpo Email Sms implementation for browse abandonment should document trigger, timing, and exclusions in merchant wiki — not only inside platform UI. Agency and contractor turnover resets programs to zero when logic lives only in flow canvas.',
        'Measure margin after discount on browse abandonment flows, not recovery or open rate alone. Finance weekly review of flow-level contribution margin catches discount treadmills before they become cultural habit.',
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Proof-first sequencing</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse email architecture</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Email one: product reminder plus education — brewing ratios for tea, weight ratings for climbing gear, pressing notes for vinyl. No code. Email two: social proof and complementary products; discount only for segments with prior discount redemption. Email three: soft incentive capped by product margin — never exceed finance floor. Full-price loyalists may never see browse discount; that protects margin on enthusiast catalogs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Newsletter overlap</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse versus editorial sends</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Newsletter subscribers who browse should not receive browse and promotional email same day. Set send priority: active browse flow suppresses generic campaign for 48 hours. Artisan coffee roasters running weekly origin newsletters need this collision rule — otherwise browse recovery feels like spam on top of editorial.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse enrollment hygiene</h2>
      <p>
        Tighten triggers quarterly. Paid social traffic inflates browse enrollments with low intent — exclude UTM sources with sub-1% browse-to-cart rate. Require logged-in view or email capture for highest-value browse paths on custom pottery and mechanical keyboard builds where AOV justifies longer nurture.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

<!-- EXPANSION_BLOCK_v2 -->

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Why browse abandonment fails on generic defaults</h2>
      <p>Shopify merchants treat browse abandonment as template toggle — enable flow, set 10% off, move on. That works until margin reports show follow product interest without discounting too early recovering revenue while destroying full-price repeat rate. Trigger discipline matters: Viewed product 2+ times or spent 60+ seconds without add-to-cart. Timing discipline matters: Email 1 at 4h with social proof; Email 2 at 48h with education; discount only in Email 3 if needed. Without exclusions, flows collide with welcome offers, replenishment reminders, and VIP early access — training subscribers to wait for stacked discounts.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Workflow test on Shopify.</strong> Sequenzy playbook encoded suppression and value-based rules for follow product interest without discounting too early without week-long flow rebuild.</p><p><strong>Scenario B — Scale merchant 900 orders/mo.</strong> Klaviyo predictive segments and holdout testing optimized browse abandonment margin after blanket discount path failed.</p><p><strong>Scenario C — Fast-start boutique.</strong> Omnisend prebuilt journey live in days; graduated when immediate discount on first browse email became recurring ops issue.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Common mistakes</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">browse abandonment anti-patterns</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]"><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Immediate discount on first browse email</li><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Recommending out-of-stock variants</li><li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Treating browse same as cart intent</li></ul>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Document collision rules in shared wiki: which flow wins when customer qualifies for cart and winback simultaneously. Test quarterly with staff accounts. Measure margin after incentive, not recovery rate alone — high recovery with negative margin is worse than no email.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Channel mix</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Email, SMS, and transactional boundaries</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Email owns narrative and education for follow product interest without discounting too early. SMS belongs as branch when mobile intent outperforms — cart recovery within four hours, drop alerts to VIP SMS-opted segments — not parallel blast to entire list. Transactional order and shipping messages stay separate; marketing suppresses when support ticket open or return in progress.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

<!-- EXPANSION_BLOCK_v3 -->

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Advanced browse abandonment patterns</h2>
      <p>After baseline follow product interest without discounting too early flow works, optimize branches: VIP holdouts without discount, engaged-but-lapsed newsletter readers versus cold buyers, subscription-active customers excluded from conflicting offers. A mechanical keyboard atelier improved browse abandonment margin 19% by routing predicted discount-sensitive profiles only to touch three — full-price loyalists stayed on education path.</p>
      <p>Holdout testing quarterly — 5% segment no promotional browse abandonment for thirty days — answers incrementality question finance actually asks. Platform attribution overstates when would-have-purchased-anyway buyers dominate converted cohort.</p>
      <p>SMS branch for browse abandonment when mobile opt-in strong: email touch one, SMS four hours if unopened for cart-adjacent workflows — never duplicate same offer both channels within two hours without measurement framework.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Cross-links</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Related workflows for browse abandonment</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">Pair browse abandonment with segmentation hygiene and discount strategy guides — flows fail when segments stale and incentives stack. Review <a class="link" href="/use-cases/segmentation">segmentation</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">discount strategy</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">collision prevention</a> when scaling send volume.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All apps →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/reviews-and-ugc">Reviews & UGC →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TOOLREVIEW_EXPANSION_v3 -->
  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Browse abandonment FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
